article.description: Sixty-one fouls marred Georgia's 83-70 victory over Vanderbilt on Saturday.
article.headline: Harrick describes ugly game as a 'root canal'
article.linkText: Sixty-one fouls mar Georgia's win over Vanderbilt
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Whistle. Groan. Free throws. Whistle. Groan. Free throws. On and on it went, foul after foul marring Georgia's 83-70 victory over Vanderbilt on Saturday. "You don't like to see it control the game,'' said Bulldogs coach Jim Harrick, whose team (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) snapped a two-game losing streak. "It was ugly, kind of like a root canal.'' Ezra Williams and Jarvis Hayes each scored 16 points for Georgia (14-7, 6-4 Southeastern Conference), but the most dominating performance was turned in by Tony Greene, Jamie Jones and Jamie Luckie -- the officiating crew. They called 61 fouls, including two technicals on Vanderbilt's Kevin Stallings that resulted in the first ejection of his 10-year coaching career. Georgia shot 45 free throws, the Commodores 37. Four players -- two for each team -- fouled out. Good thing the game didn't go to overtime, since six other players finished with four fouls apiece. The crowd at Stegeman Coliseum expressed its frustration by chanting, "Let them play!'' One fan yelled at the officials, "We came to see them, not you!'' "It seemed like they stopped play every time,'' Harrick said. "It's really hard to play like that. But we made some baskets when we needed to.'' The Bulldogs avenged a Jan. 29 loss to Vanderbilt (10-12, 3-8) and handed the Commodores their fourth straight loss. Vanderbilt's top two scorers, Matt Freije and Brian Thornton, were both plagued by foul trouble. Freije picked up his fourth foul early in the second half, played only 19 minutes and finished with eight points -- 10 below his average. Thornton, averaging 13.6 points, played just 16 minutes before fouling out with seven points. "It's real hard to get in a rhythm, especially when you're sitting on the bench,'' said Freije, who made only 2-of-10 shots. "That's where I sat nearly the entire game.'' Stallings finally boiled over as he sat alongside his two best players. He complained about a call with 16:13 remaining and drew two technicals from Greene in rapid succession, an automatic ejection. Richard Wehunt hit four straight free throws to give the Bulldogs a 48-32 lead. "I was just trying to stand up for my players,'' Stallings said. "I'm looking at my best players with four fouls, two of which I had to shake my head at. People might think I was frustrated, but I wasn't. My players just needed someone to fight for them.'' Georgia led 33-28 at halftime and started the second half with a 9-0 run. Chris Daniels sparked the outburst, going in for a dunk after a steal, setting up a layup by Steve Thomas with a nice pass and tipping in a miss by Hayes. Daniels finished with 13 points, eight rebounds, five steals and three assists. Jonas Hayes provided a spark off the bench with 11 points. The Bulldogs held Vanderbilt to 20-of-59 (34 percent) from the field and held a commanding 48-38 advantage on the boards. "I thought our defensive intensity was outstanding,'' Harrick said. "That was something we worked on all week.'' Still, Vanderbilt managed to hang around for much of the second half. The Commodores got as close as four points a couple of times, but Georgia pulled away in the final two minutes. Hayes hit a jumper, then made a stunning no-look pass to Williams that set up a rim-rattling dunk. "Vandy has a good, scrappy team,'' Jarvis Hayes said. "I felt like we should have put them away when Freije was out, but they stayed in it. We had to buckle down to win the game.'' Corey Smith led the Commodores with 14 points. Freshman Julian Terrell added 13 points and 11 rebounds -- both career highs -- but his performance was marred by a 3-of-9 showing at the foul line. Georgia came into the game having lost three of four, a slump that began with a 94-91 loss at Vanderbilt. The two teams are used to playing physical games -- 44 fouls were called in the first meeting. "Sixty fouls,'' Jonas Hayes said, shaking his head. "But you've got to get past that. The refs did what they have to do, and we did what we have to do.''
